BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 190.8 720 Td (Chapter 4: Battery Power) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (Zara was curious about the batteries in her flashlight. How do they work?) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td ('A battery stores chemical energy and converts it to electrical energy!') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td (She read that inside are chemicals that react, pushing electrons through the wire.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td ('The positive end \(+\) pulls electrons in, and the negative end \(-\) pushes them out.') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td ('When the chemicals are used up, the battery dies - no more electron push!') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td ('Rechargeable batteries can reverse the chemical reaction!' Zara was impressed.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE: HOW BATTERIES WORK) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (Batteries convert stored chemical energy into electrical energy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (Inside are two different materials \(electrodes\) and a chemical paste \(electrolyte\).) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (A chemical reaction at the anode \(-\) releases electrons that travel through the circuit.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Electrons arrive at the cathode \(+\) where another reaction absorbs them.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (When the chemicals are completely reacted, the battery is 'dead.') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 464 Td (Rechargeable batteries use a reverse current to undo the chemical reaction!) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 374 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 433 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 413 Td (* The first battery was invented in 1800 by Alessandro Volta \(that is where 'volt' comes from!\).) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 395 Td (* A potato can make a tiny battery! The acid reacts with zinc and copper electrodes.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 377 Td (* Electric car batteries can weigh 1,000 pounds and contain thousands of small cells.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 344 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 328 Td (Make a 'lemon battery': push a copper penny and a zinc nail into a lemon. Measure voltage with a multimeter!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 308 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 292 Td (Why do batteries eventually run out of power? What is being used up inside?) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
